  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several important legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- First major case establishing corporate criminal liability for Bank Secrecy Act violations\n- Set precedent for financial institutions' reporting requirements\n\n2. United States v. BCCI (1991)\n- Landmark case involving international bank fraud and money laundering\n- Resulted in significant penalties and regulatory reforms\n\n3. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Established comprehensive framework for money laundering prosecutions\n- Expanded definition of money laundering offenses\n\n4. Bank Secrecy Act (USA)\n- Established reporting requirements for financial transactions\n- Provides legal basis for investigating potential money laundering\n\n5. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- International standards for anti-money laundering compliance\n- Influenced legal frameworks globally\n\nThese cases and regulations have shaped modern anti-money laundering legal approaches. Would you like me to elaborate on any specific precedent?\n\nNote: I aim to provide factual legal information without making specific claims about ongoing cases.",
